Chapter 7: Lattice‑Based Graceful Degradation

7.1 Health Lattice
Let $\mathcal{H}$ be a finite lattice with partial order $\preceq$, where $h_1 \preceq h_2$ means $h_1$ is less healthy than $h_2$. For autonomous robots, we instantiate $\mathcal{H}$ as:

· nominal – Full capability.
· degraded – Minor sensor/actuator noise.
· critical – Loss of non‑essential subsystems.
· failure – Safety‑critical failure.

The Hasse diagram is a chain: nominal $\succ$ degraded $\succ$ critical $\succ$ failure.

7.2 Diagnostic Predicates and Transition Rules
The monitor determines health by evaluating predicates over sensor data. Table 7.1 defines the mapping.

Sensor/Actuator Event Diagnostic Predicate Health State AES Level Operational Constraint
Nominal operation SNR > 20 dB ∧ Lat < 10 ms nominal Gold Unrestricted swarm ops
Event camera drift Var($f_{\text{events}}$) > $\theta_{\text{drift}}$ degraded Silver Max velocity ≤ 50 %
LiDAR occlusion $\sum$ Points < threshold critical Bronze E‑stop enabled / human‑in‑loop
Motor stall / IMU loss $I_{\text{motor}} > I_{\text{max}}$ ∨ no heartbeat failure None Immediate safe state

7.3 Monotone Certification
Define $\mathsf{certify}: \mathcal{H} \to \{\text{Gold},\text{Silver},\text{Bronze},\text{None}\}$ as above. The function is monotone non‑increasing: if $h_1 \preceq h_2$ then $\mathsf{certify}(h_1) \le \mathsf{certify}(h_2)$.

Theorem 5 (Safety under Degradation). For an agent satisfying the AES compliance formulas for a given health state $h$, if its health degrades to $h' \preceq h$, then the agent remains compliant at the certification level $\mathsf{certify}(h')$, provided it continues to satisfy the same LTL formulas (with the appropriate health‑related atomic propositions).

Proof. By monotonicity, $\mathsf{certify}(h') \le \mathsf{certify}(h)$. The agent’s behavior under degraded health is a subset of its possible behaviors under the higher health (since it may have fewer capabilities). Hence, if it satisfied the safety and liveness properties before, it still does after degradation. ∎

7.4 Mechanized Proof in Lean 4
We formalize the health lattice, certification levels, and the monotonicity theorem in Lean 4.

```lean
import Mathlib.Order.Lattice
import Mathlib.Order.GaloisConnection

inductive HealthState where
  | nominal
  | degraded
  | critical
  | failure
  deriving DecidableEq

instance : PartialOrder HealthState where
  le h1 h2 := match h1, h2 with
    | .failure, _          => true
    | .critical, .critical => true
    | .critical, .degraded => true
    | .critical, .nominal  => true
    | .degraded, .degraded => true
    | .degraded, .nominal  => true
    | .nominal, .nominal   => true
    | _, _                 => false
  le_refl := by intro h; cases h <;> simp [PartialOrder.le]
  le_trans := by intro a b c h1 h2; cases a <;> cases b <;> cases c <;> simp_all [PartialOrder.le]
  le_antisymm := by intro a b h1 h2; cases a <;> cases b <;> simp_all [PartialOrder.le]

inductive CertLevel where
  | none
  | bronze
  | silver
  | gold
  deriving DecidableEq

instance : PartialOrder CertLevel where
  le c1 c2 := match c1, c2 with
    | .none, _           => true
    | .bronze, .bronze   => true
    | .bronze, .silver   => true
    | .bronze, .gold     => true
    | .silver, .silver   => true
    | .silver, .gold     => true
    | .gold, .gold       => true
    | _, _               => false
  le_refl := by intro c; cases c <;> simp
  le_trans := by intro a b c h1 h2; cases a <;> cases b <;> cases c <;> simp_all
  le_antisymm := by intro a b h1 h2; cases a <;> cases b <;> simp_all

def certify (h : HealthState) : CertLevel :=
  match h with
  | .nominal  => .gold
  | .degraded => .silver
  | .critical => .bronze
  | .failure  => .none

theorem safety_monotone (h1 h2 : HealthState) (h_le : h1 ≤ h2) :
    certify h1 ≤ certify h2 := by
  cases h1 <;> cases h2 <;> simp_all [certify, PartialOrder.le]
```

