Chapter 8: Runtime Monitor Construction – Deterministic Case

8.1 Monitor for $\varphi_{\text{live}}$ with Fairness
We construct a monitor for the nested bounded liveness formula that also respects the fairness assumption. The monitor maintains a queue of timers, each a 4‑tuple $(t_{\text{obs}}, t_{\text{plan}}, t_{\text{act}}, t_{\text{learn}})$ initialized to $(k,k,k,k)$. The transition function $\delta$ and verdict function $v$ are as follows:

· When a new input arrives ($p_{\text{in}}$ true), a new timer is enqueued.
· At each step, if $p_{\text{res}}$ is true, all active timers decrement their first non‑zero counter. If $p_{\text{res}}$ is false, timers are frozen.
· If a timer’s counter reaches zero while still active, the monitor outputs $\bot$ (violation) because the deadline was missed under available resources.
· When an agent completes a phase, the corresponding counter is reset to zero (or the timer advances to the next phase).
· When all counters of the front timer are zero, it is dequeued.
· If the queue becomes empty, the monitor outputs $\top$ (satisfaction).
· Otherwise, the verdict is pending.

8.2 Monitor Correctness

Theorem 6 (Monitor Correctness under Fairness). Let $\sigma$ be an infinite trace. Define the monitor $M$ with frozen timers as above. Then:

· If $M$ outputs $\bot$ at position $i$, then there exists a fairness‑satisfying extension of $\sigma[0..i]$ that violates $\varphi_{\text{live}}$.
· If $M$ outputs $\top$ at position $i$, then every fairness‑satisfying extension satisfies $\varphi_{\text{live}}$.
· Otherwise, the verdict is $\top_p$ (pending satisfaction) or $\bot_p$ (pending violation) according to the 4‑valued semantics.

Proof. The proof follows by induction on the length of the prefix. The base case (empty prefix) gives pending satisfaction. For the inductive step, consider the last event. The key insight is that when a timer expires (reaches zero) while $p_{\text{res}}$ holds, the agent has had a full window of resource availability to complete the phase but failed; thus no fairness‑satisfying extension can later complete that input’s chain within the deadline. Conversely, if the queue empties, all pending inputs have been completed, and any future input cannot affect those already finished; thus all extensions satisfy the formula. The cases where $p_{\text{res}}$ is false cause no timer advancement, preserving the pending status. ∎

8.3 State Complexity
For a single input ($m=1$), the minimal DFA that tracks the distance to failure in each phase has exactly $4k+2$ states. For $m$ overlapping inputs, the queue size is bounded by $m$, and each timer can be in at most $4k+1$ distinct states (active with counter values, completed, expired). Hence the total number of monitor states is $\mathcal{O}((4k+2)^m)$.

