Chapter 9: Compositional Verification with Trust

9.1 Trust‑Weighted Contracts
We consider a system of agents with acyclic dependencies. Each agent $a$ has a certification level $\mathsf{Cert}(a) \in \{\text{Gold},\text{Silver},\text{Bronze},\text{None}\}$. We define a trust relation: a Gold agent may only trust inputs from agents with certification at least Silver; a Silver agent trusts Bronze, etc. For each agent $a$, we define an assumption $A_a$ that includes conditions on the certification levels of its peers. For example:

$A_a \equiv \bigwedge_{b \in \text{inputs}(a)} \bigl( \mathsf{Cert}(b) \ge \text{Silver} \rightarrow \varphi_{\text{safe}}(b) \bigr)$.

Additionally, Gold agents are equipped with a refusal primitive: if an input from an untrusted source does not satisfy a specified safety property, the agent may ignore that input (treat it as a no‑op).

9.2 Composition Theorem
We impose an acyclic ordering on agents such that the assumptions of an agent only refer to agents of lower order. For each agent $a$, we prove that under its assumption $A_a$, it satisfies its guarantee $G_a$ (the AES compliance formulas appropriate to its certification level). For Gold agents, the guarantee includes the ability to safely ignore non‑compliant inputs.

Theorem 7 (Trust‑Weighted Compositional Correctness). Under the acyclic ordering and the trust‑based assumptions, if for every agent $a$ we have $A_a \models G_a$, then the composition of all agents satisfies $\bigwedge_a G_a$ even in the presence of non‑certified agents, provided Gold agents exercise their refusal primitive.

Proof. By induction on the order. For the base case (agents with no inputs), the result holds trivially. Assume the property holds for all agents of order $< i$. Consider an agent $a$ of order $i$. Its assumptions $A_a$ only refer to agents of lower order, which by induction satisfy their guarantees. Hence the environment of $a$ satisfies $A_a$, and by the local proof $a$ satisfies $G_a$. For Gold agents, if a lower‑order agent $b$ is non‑certified, its inputs are not trusted; the refusal primitive ensures that $a$ treats those inputs as absent, so its behavior is as if $b$ did not exist. Thus $G_a$ holds regardless of $b$’s compliance. ∎

9.3 Refusal Primitive Implementation
The refusal primitive is implemented by augmenting the perception phase with a filter: for each input from a peer $b$, if $\mathsf{Cert}(b)$ is below the required trust level, the agent checks a predicate $\psi_{\text{safe}}(b)$ (e.g., whether the input conforms to a known safety envelope). If $\psi_{\text{safe}}(b)$ is false, the input is discarded and treated as $p_{\text{in}} = \bot$. This ensures that the agent’s state update only considers trusted information.

